import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
sns.set()

pd.set_option('display.max_rows', None)
pd.set_option('display.max_columns', None)
pd.set_option('display.width', None)
pd.set_option('display.max_colwidth', None)

# === Setting  target names ===
TARGET_F = "TARGET_BAD_FLAG"
TARGET_A = "TARGET_LOSS_AMT"

# === Loading HMEQ dataset ===
INFILE = "HMEQ_Loss.csv"
df = pd.read_csv(INFILE)

# === Summary of data types
print(df.dtypes)

# === Summary of statistics
print(df.describe().T)

# === Splitting variables by type ===
dt = df.dtypes
objList, intList, floatList = [], [], []

for i in dt.index:
    if i in [TARGET_F, TARGET_A]: continue
    if dt[i] == "object":
        objList.append(i)
    elif dt[i] == "int64":
        intList.append(i)
    elif dt[i] == "float64":
        floatList.append(i)

print("\nOBJECT COLUMNS:\n", objList)
print("\nINTEGER COLUMNS:\n", intList)
print("\nFLOAT COLUMNS:\n", floatList)

# === Categorical variables
for col in objList:
    print(f"\nClass = {col}")
    g = df.groupby(col)
    print("Crash Prob:\n", g[TARGET_F].mean())
    print("Loss Amount:\n", g[TARGET_A].mean())

# === Continuous variables
print("\n--- INTEGER VARIABLES ---")
for col in intList:
    print(f"\nVariable = {col}")
    print("Avg by Default Flag:\n", df.groupby(TARGET_F)[col].mean())
    print("Correlation with Loss:", round(100 * df[col].corr(df[TARGET_A]), 1), "%")

print("\n--- FLOAT VARIABLES ---")
for col in floatList:
    print(f"\nVariable = {col}")
    print("Avg by Default Flag:\n", df.groupby(TARGET_F)[col].mean())
    print("Correlation with Loss:", round(100 * df[col].corr(df[TARGET_A]), 1), "%")

# === Pie Charts (no overlap)
for col in objList:
    x = df[col].value_counts(dropna=False)
    labels = x.index.tolist()
    sizes = x.tolist()

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.pie(sizes, labels=labels, startangle=90, shadow=True, autopct="%1.1f%%",
        labeldistance=1.1,
        pctdistance=0.7,
        textprops={'fontsize': 8, 'ha': 'center'}
    )

    plt.title("Pie Chart: " + col)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# === Histograms
for col in intList + floatList:
    plt.hist(df[col].dropna(), bins=30)
    plt.title(f"Histogram: {col}")
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.show()

plt.hist(df[TARGET_A].dropna(), bins=50)
plt.title("Histogram: Loss Amount")
plt.xlabel("TARGET_LOSS_AMT")
plt.show()

# ========================================
# === HANDLE MISSING DATA & ENCODING ===
# ========================================

# === Imputing numeric fields & creating missing flags
num_cols = intList + floatList
for col in num_cols:
    if df[col].isnull().sum() > 0:
        df["FLAG_" + col] = df[col].isnull().astype(int)
        df["IMP_" + col] = df[col].fillna(df[col].median())
        df.drop(columns=col, inplace=True)
    else:
        df.rename(columns={col: "IMP_" + col}, inplace=True)

# === Imputing categorical fields with "MISSING"
for col in objList:
    if df[col].isnull().sum() > 0:
        newcol = "IMP_" + col
        df[newcol] = df[col].fillna("MISSING")
        df.drop(columns=col, inplace=True)
    else:
        df.rename(columns={col: "IMP_" + col}, inplace=True)

# === Updating object list after renaming/imputing
dt = df.dtypes
objList = [col for col in dt.index if col.startswith("IMP_") and dt[col] == "object"]

# === Feature engineering: education tiers
if "IMP_EDUCATION" in df.columns:
    df["y_EDU_4"] = df["IMP_EDUCATION"].isin(["a_PhD"]).astype(int)
    df["y_EDU_3"] = df["IMP_EDUCATION"].isin(["a_PhD", "b_Masters"]).astype(int)
    df["y_EDU_2"] = df["IMP_EDUCATION"].isin(["a_PhD", "b_Masters", "c_Bachelors"]).astype(int)
    df["y_EDU_1"] = df["IMP_EDUCATION"].isin(["a_PhD", "b_Masters", "c_Bachelors", "d_High School"]).astype(int)
    df.drop(columns="IMP_EDUCATION", inplace=True)

# === Feature engineering: white collar jobs
if "IMP_JOB" in df.columns:
    df["z_IMP_JOB_WhiteCollar"] = df["IMP_JOB"].isin(["Manager", "Professional", "Lawyer", "Doctor"]).astype(int)

# === One-hot encode remaining categoricals (using 0/1)
for col in objList:
    if col in df.columns:
        dummies = pd.get_dummies(df[col], prefix="z_" + col, drop_first=True, dtype=int)
        df = pd.concat([df, dummies], axis=1)
        df.drop(columns=col, inplace=True)

# === Final column sort and target ordering
df = df[sorted(df.columns)]
df.insert(0, TARGET_A, df.pop(TARGET_A))
df.insert(0, TARGET_F, df.pop(TARGET_F))

# === Final check
print("\n\nFinal processed dataset preview:\n")
print(df.head(4).T)

"""
DECISION TREE
"""

def getTreeVars( TREE, varNames ) :
   tree_ = TREE.tree_
   varName = [ varNames[i] if i != _tree.TREE_UNDEFINED else "undefined!" for i in tree_.feature ]

   nameSet = set()
   for i in tree_.feature :
       if i != _tree.TREE_UNDEFINED :
           nameSet.add( i )
   nameList = list( nameSet )
   parameter_list = list()
   for i in nameList :
       parameter_list.append( varNames[i] )
   return parameter_list

"""
RANDOM FOREST
"""

def getEnsembleTreeVars( ENSTREE, varNames ) :
   importance = ENSTREE.feature_importances_
   index = np.argsort(importance)
   theList = []
   for i in index :
       imp_val = importance[i]
       if imp_val > np.average( ENSTREE.feature_importances_ ) :
           v = int( imp_val / np.max( ENSTREE.feature_importances_ ) * 100 )
           theList.append( ( varNames[i], v ) )
   theList = sorted(theList,key=itemgetter(1),reverse=True)
   return theList

# Try different thresholds

    preds = (probs >= t).astype(int)
    acc = metrics.accuracy_score(Y_test[TARGET_F], preds)
    print(f"Threshold = {t:.1f} --> Accuracy = {acc:.4f}")


#BINGO BONUS !!!

#Running the Gradient Boosting model 3 times
#to see which variables show up as most important each time.


from collections import Counter

top_vars = []

for seed in range(3):
    X_train_temp, X_test_temp, Y_train_temp, Y_test_temp = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.2, random_state=seed)
    model = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=seed)
    model.fit(X_train_temp, Y_train_temp[TARGET_F])
    vars_used = [v[0] for v in getEnsembleTreeVars(model, list(X.columns))]
    top_vars.extend(vars_used)

# Count which variables appeared most
counts = Counter(top_vars)
print("\nMost consistent predictors across 3 runs:")
for var, count in counts.most_common(5):
    print(f"{var}: {count} time")
